The White House has announced the appointment of 13 individuals to serve as White House Fellows for the 2010-2011 year. The Fellows come from diverse backgrounds and professions and have shown a strong commitment to public service and leadership. The program, created in 1964, aims to give promising American leaders firsthand experience with the workings of the Federal government and to encourage active citizenship and service to the nation. The Fellows will also participate in an education program to broaden their knowledge of leadership, policy formulation, military operations, and current affairs. Selection is highly competitive and based on professional achievement, leadership potential, commitment to public service, and the necessary knowledge and skills to contribute at the highest levels of the government.